result.execSummary:
The defendant Victoria L Mahl was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Original Warrant has been received and destroyed
from Clerk to Defendant re: Court-ordered payment plan
Warrant was canceled.  Talked to Dave at GLSO.
Defendant in custody and present in court via video from the Green Lake County Jail and without counsel.

1:12 p.m.  Defendant in custody and present in court via video from the Green Lake County Jail and without counsel.  FTP $544.00.  Statement by the defendant.  Court questions defendant regarding payment.  Statement by defendant - can make her first payment when she gets her first paycheck.  Court orders defendant to pay $10.00 by February 15, 2016 and every 2 weeks thereafter.  Court orders a warrant and stays that pending compliance.

Court adjourned at 1:15 p.m.
from Clerk to Defendant re: Payment Arrangements

1:10 p.m.  Defendant appears in court.
Defendant makes statement.
Court orders warrant - stayed.  Defendant to pay a minimum of $10 every other week commencing Nov. 27, 2015.  Warrant to be issued if defendant does not make payment.
Court adjourned 1:17 p.m.

9:34 a.m.  Defendant present in court without counsel.  Lisa Vanden Branden for the State of Wisconsin.  Court recites agreement - defendant will plea to count 1 as charged with a fine and costs.  State concurs.  Defendant concurs.  Court goes over right to counsel.  Defendant waives right to counsel.  Court accepts waiver.

Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - defendant waives these rights.  Court goes over the elements of each offense.  Court instructs defendant of the maximum penalty.  Court instructs defendant regarding deportation.

Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST.  Court finds the plea is made freely, voluntarily, intelligently and understandingly.  Court finds there is a factual basis to support the plea.  Court finds the defendant guilty on count 1 as charged.  Court orders the judgment of conviction be entered here today.  ADA confirms compliance with victim witness rights.  Sentencing statement by ADA.   No statement by the defendant.

Court sentences the defendant to: $100 fine plus court costs.  Court grants the defendant 60 days to pay or payment plan.  Defendant to submit a DNA Sample.

Court adjourned at 9:39 a.m.

9:47 a.m.  Defendant present in court without counsel.  Lisa Vanden Branden for the State of Wisconsin.  Statement by defendant - will not be getting an attorney.  Court goes over right to counsel.  Defendant waives right to counsel.  Court accepts waiver.  Court will set for status hearing on July 21, 2015 at 9:30 a.m.  Defendant to make appointment with the DA's office.

Court adjourned at 9:48 a.m.
Defendant is to complete processing with the Green Lake County Sheriff's Department.
Defendant is to complete processing with the Green Lake County Sheriff's Department.

1:36 p.m.Defendant present in court without counsel.  Andrew Christenson for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant confirms receipt of the criminal complaint and waives reading.  Court instructs the defendant of the maximum penalty on each count.  Court finds probable cause.  Court instructs the defendant of his right to an attorney.  Defendant enters a plea of NOT GUILTY.  DA makes bond recommendation.  Court sets bond at $500 signature bond and conditions of:  Defendant is to complete processing with the Green Lake County Sheriff's Department.  Court will set for Status Hearing on July 7, 2015 at 9:30 a.m.  Statement by the Court - grants parties ten days to request recusal.

Court adjourned at 1:38 p.m.
